post_cb({"12590626": {"ParentId": "12590255", "CommentCount": "7", "Body": "<p>The macro relates to the value of the unicode character when this is stored in wchar_t. </p>\n<p>More specifically, ISO/IEC 10646 standard supports more characters as ammendments are made to the standard. </p>\n<p>The year and month that you can define as a value to the macro mean that when you store a Unicode character to a wchar_t variable, then the value of the unicode character that will be stored in that variable will be the one that was in effect in the given year and month. </p>\n<p>See here <code>[http://www.unicode.org/charts/][1]</code> for a reference of Unicode short identifiers</p>\n<p>Hope this helps</p>\n<p>Lefteris</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "1627113", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "12590626", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2012-09-25T20:35:38.253", "LastActivityDate": "2012-09-25T20:35:38.253"}, "12590255": {"CommentCount": "2", "ViewCount": "1313", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "906773", "CreationDate": "2012-09-25T20:04:53.680", "LastActivityDate": "2012-09-25T20:35:38.253", "Title": "What does __STDC_ISO_10646__ exactly mean?", "AcceptedAnswerId": "12590458", "LastEditDate": "2012-09-25T20:22:09.990", "Id": "12590255", "Score": "4", "Body": "<p>I'm having a hard time understanding the macro <code>__STDC_ISO_10646__</code>, from my copy of the C++ standard:</p>\n<p><code>__STDC_ISO_10646__</code></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_12590255_12590255_0\">An integer constant of the form yyyymmL (for example, 199712L). If\n  this symbol is defined, then every character in the Unicode required\n  set, when stored in an object of type wchar_t, has the same value as\n  the short identifier of that character. The Unicode required set\n  consists of all the characters that are defined by ISO/IEC 10646,\n  along with all amendments and technical corrigenda as of the specified\n  year and month.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>From my understanding, this means <code>wchar_t</code> on your system would represent a unicode code point. Is this correct? If this is the case, then utf-8 and utf-16 encoding would not be conforming and utf-32 would be conforming right?. Also, what other character encodings are conforming?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><unicode>", "OwnerUserId": "906773", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_12590255_12590458_0": {"section_id": 551, "quality": 0.8571428571428571, "length": 6}, "so_12590255_12590255_0": {"section_id": 551, "quality": 0.9285714285714286, "length": 39}}, "n3337": {"so_12590255_12590458_0": {"section_id": 542, "quality": 0.8571428571428571, "length": 6}, "so_12590255_12590255_0": {"section_id": 542, "quality": 0.9523809523809523, "length": 40}}, "n4659": {"so_12590255_12590458_0": {"section_id": 572, "quality": 0.8571428571428571, "length": 6}, "so_12590255_12590255_0": {"section_id": 572, "quality": 0.9285714285714286, "length": 39}}}, "12590458": {"ParentId": "12590255", "CommentCount": "5", "Body": "<p>The section of the standard you quote (\u00a716.8 Predefined macro names [cpp.predefined]) prefixes the series of definitions with:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_12590255_12590458_0\">\u00b62 The following macro names are conditionally defined by the implementation:</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>That means that if the implementation can't meet the requirements (e.g. because <code>wchar_t</code> is a 16-bit type), then the implementation will not define <code>__STDC_ISO_10646__</code>.</p>\n<p>On the other hand, if <code>wchar_t</code> is a 32-bit or larger type, then the implementation may well be able to define the macro.  ISO 10646 only requires 21 bits to represent all the characters, but for (almost) all practical purposes, that means that 16-bit <code>wchar_t</code> is too small and 32-bit <code>wchar_t</code> is amply big enough.  It also means an implementation from scratch is likely to make <code>wchar_t</code> into a 32-bit type.  Pre-existing implementations may be hobbled by backwards compatibility if they chose a 16-bit <code>wchar_t</code> before this option was standardized.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "15168", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "12590458", "Score": "4", "CreationDate": "2012-09-25T20:21:26.583", "LastActivityDate": "2012-09-25T20:21:26.583"}});